Build ID: M20060921-0945

Steps To Reproduce:
1. add MaxDB-JDBC driver as "Generic JDBC driver"
2. create connection to database
3. try to edit data of table
4. save

Then an error will arise:
com.sap.dbtech.jdbc.exceptions.DatabaseException: [-5006] (at 37): Missing identifier
Error saving data
Inserted 0 row(s)
Updated 0 row(s)
Deleted 0 row(s)

And in the SQL-Results view, the column "Operation" says `DJH`.`KM_BASE_AUSGABEN` - which is wrong. MaxDB doesn't use `  to quote identifiers. It uses the " character, which is correctly returned by Connection.getIdentifierQuoteString().


More information:
Here is, how i quote identifier names:

public String quoteIdentifier(Connection conn, String t) throws SQLException
{
  DatabaseMetaData dmd = conn.getMetaData();
  String quote = dmd.getIdentifierQuoteString();
  if (t.indexOf(quote) < 0)
  {
    t = t.toUpperCase(); // SAPDB hack
    return quote + t + quote;
  }
  throw new SQLException("illegal table name");
}


This method allows quoting of all identifier, that don't contain the quote-character/string itself. For that case, JDBC doesn't provide any standard way and the method above will throw an Exception.



BTW: there are more functions, like Connection.getCatalogSeperaot() which like to be used if that is not already the case ;-)

Sorry, another mistake:

please delete the line "t = t.toUpperCase(); // SAPDB hack".
It's not needed in general and actually would do harm.

So the method should read:


public String quoteIdentifier(Connection conn, String t) throws SQLException
{
  DatabaseMetaData dmd = conn.getMetaData();
  String quote = dmd.getIdentifierQuoteString();
  if (t.indexOf(quote) < 0)
  {
    return quote + t + quote;
  }
  throw new SQLException("illegal table name");
}

2.0M3 StaleGenModel Detector has the very honest comment:
/* HACK * @see ModelImporter#saveGenModelAndEPackages * saves both ecore and genmodel files regardless of the fact .ecore was not modified, * hence, we adjust the timestamp to avoid false stale detection */ if (new Date(genModelTimeStamp.getTime() + 3000).before(ts)) {
However: saveGenModelAndEPackages computes a list of resources to save genmodel-first, so on my not so new PC with a moderate size genmodel and a two-resource domain model, there can be a 7 second delay from genmodel to Ecore timestamp. i.e. more than the 3 second hack.
This could be rescued by computing the resource save list genmodel-last.
However, it should be possible to work with read-only ecore and genmodel files to ensure that no inadvertant changes are made to shared/third-party models.
So don't hack the hack, just remove the original bug. Only dirty resources need saving.

